Let Alg be a deterministic online algorithm for some minimization problem P. We say that Alg is c-competitive if there exists α ≥ 0 such that Alg(σ) ≤ c·Opt(σ) + α for any instance σ. Claim: If an online algorithm Alg is c-competitive with additive constant α, then it is also (c+1)-competitive with additive constant 0.

In the ski rental problem, we have a parameter b > 1 representing the cost to buy ski equipment, while renting costs 1 EUR per day. Consider a deterministic algorithm that rents for exactly ⌊b/2⌋ days and then buys. Claim: This algorithm achieves a competitive ratio of at most 2.

Let Alg be any online marking algorithm for the paging problem with N pages and cache size k. We learned that Alg is k-competitive. Claim: Every marking algorithm has the same competitive ratio of exactly k.

Consider the online paging problem with N = k + 2 pages and cache size k. Let RandMark be the randomized marking algorithm that evicts an unmarked page chosen uniformly at random on each page fault. Claim: The competitive ratio of RandMark for this setting is O(log k).

Consider the UnifMTS algorithm on a uniform metric space with n points. During a phase, let s_1,...,s_n be the states ordered by non-decreasing saturation times. Claim: The algorithm can move from an unsaturated state to a saturated state within the same phase.

We say a metric space M has tree-width w if it can be isometrically embedded in a metric space obtained from distances in a tree with at most w leaves. Claim: There exists a deterministic online MTS algorithm with competitive ratio O(w) for metric spaces with tree-width w.

In the online Steiner tree problem, terminals arrive one by one and must be connected to the growing tree. Consider an instance where all terminals lie on a path graph. Claim: Any deterministic online algorithm has competitive ratio Ω(log n) even when the terminals form a path in the underlying graph.
Consider a metric space M obtained from distances in an unweighted complete graph K_n. Claim: M can be probabilistically embedded in tree metric spaces with distortion O(1).

In the χ-assisted online paging problem, let η(h,σ) denote the prediction error of predictor h on sequence σ. A predictor h is χ-accurate if η(h,σ) ≤ χ·Opt(σ) for all sequences σ. Claim: The PredMark algorithm achieves competitive ratio O(√χ) when using any χ-accurate predictor.

Let σ be a request sequence for online paging with N pages and cache size k. The sequence is partitioned into phases where each phase contains at most k distinct page requests. Claim: If a phase contains exactly k distinct page requests, then the next phase must begin with a request for a page not seen in the current phase.

Let H_k = 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + ... + 1/k be the k-th harmonic number. We know that ln k < H_k ≤ 1 + ln k. Claim: For the RandMark algorithm, the expected number of page faults in a phase with m_i fresh pages is exactly m_i · H_k.
Consider a traversal algorithm for MTS on a 2-point metric space with distance δ(1,2) = 1. The algorithm alternates between states 1 and 2. Claim: This traversal algorithm is exactly 4-competitive.

A finite metric space M = (V,δ) has aspect ratio equal to max_{x,y∈V} δ(x,y) / min_{x≠y∈V} δ(x,y). Claim: Any metric space with aspect ratio ρ can be embedded in a uniform metric space with distortion at most ρ.
Consider the online paging problem with N = k+1 pages and cache size k. Claim: There exists a deterministic online algorithm with competitive ratio strictly less than k for this setting.

Yao's principle provides a method to establish lower bounds for randomized online algorithms by analyzing the performance of deterministic algorithms against a carefully chosen probability distribution over inputs. Claim: If we can show that every deterministic algorithm has expected cost at least c·E[Opt] under some input distribution, then every randomized algorithm has competitive ratio at least c.

Claim: If an online algorithm Alg is c-competitive with additive constant α, then it is also (c+1)-competitive with additive constant 0.

Let Alg be any online marking algorithm for the paging problem with N pages and cache size k. We learned that Alg is k-competitive. Claim: Every marking algorithm has the same competitive ratio of exactly k.

Consider the online paging problem with N = k + 2 pages and cache size k. Let RandMark be the randomized marking algorithm that evicts an unmarked page chosen uniformly at random on each page fault. Claim: The competitive ratio of RandMark for this setting is O(log k).

Consider the UnifMTS algorithm on a uniform metric space with n points. During a phase, let s_1,...,s_n be the states ordered by non-decreasing saturation times. Claim: The algorithm can move from an unsaturated state to a saturated state within the same phase.

We say a metric space M has tree-width w if it can be isometrically embedded in a metric space obtained from distances in a tree with at most w leaves. Claim: There exists a deterministic online MTS algorithm with competitive ratio O(w) for metric spaces with tree-width w.

In the online Steiner tree problem, terminals arrive one by one and must be connected to the growing tree. Consider an instance where all terminals lie on a path graph. Claim: Any deterministic online algorithm has competitive ratio Ω(log n) even when the terminals form a path in the underlying graph.
Consider a metric space M obtained from distances in an unweighted complete graph K_n. Claim: M can be probabilistically embedded in tree metric spaces with distortion O(1).

In the χ-assisted online paging problem, let η(h,σ) denote the prediction error of predictor h on sequence σ. A predictor h is χ-accurate if η(h,σ) ≤ χ·Opt(σ) for all sequences σ. Claim: The PredMark algorithm achieves competitive ratio O(√χ) when using any χ-accurate predictor.

Let σ be a request sequence for online paging with N pages and cache size k. The sequence is partitioned into phases where each phase contains at most k distinct page requests. Consider a traversal algorithm for MTS on a 2-point metric space with distance δ(1,2) = 1. The algorithm alternates between states 1 and 2. Claim: This traversal algorithm is exactly 4-competitive.

Let Alg be any online marking algorithm for the paging problem with N pages and cache size k. We learned that Alg is k-competitive. Claim: Every marking algorithm has the same competitive ratio of exactly k.

Let Alg be a deterministic online algorithm for some minimization problem P. We say that Alg is c-competitive if there exists α ≥ 0 such that Alg(σ) ≤ c·Opt(σ) + α for any instance σ. Claim: If an online algorithm Alg is c-competitive with additive constant α, then it is also (c+1)-competitive with additive constant 0.

In the ski rental problem, we have a parameter b > 1 representing the cost to buy ski equipment, while renting costs 1 EUR per day. Consider a deterministic algorithm that rents for exactly ⌊b/2⌋ days and then buys. Claim: This algorithm achieves a competitive ratio of at most 2.

Let Alg be any online marking algorithm for the paging problem with N pages and cache size k. We learned that Alg is k-competitive. Claim: Every marking algorithm has the same competitive ratio of exactly k.

Consider the online paging problem with N = k + 2 pages and cache size k. Let RandMark be the randomized marking algorithm that evicts an unmarked page chosen uniformly at random on each page fault. Claim: The competitive ratio of RandMark for this setting is O(log k).

Consider the UnifMTS algorithm on a uniform metric space with n points. During a phase, let s_1,...,s_n be the states ordered by non-decreasing saturation times. Claim: The algorithm can move from an unsaturated state to a saturated state within the same phase.

We say a metric space M has tree-width w if it can be isometrically embedded in a metric space obtained from distances in a tree with at most w leaves. Claim: There exists a deterministic online MTS algorithm with competitive ratio O(w) for metric spaces with tree-width w.

In the online Steiner tree problem, terminals arrive one by one and must be connected to the growing tree. Consider an instance where all terminals lie on a path graph. Claim: Any deterministic online algorithm has competitive ratio Ω(log n) even when the terminals form a path in the underlying graph.
Consider a metric space M obtained from distances in an unweighted complete graph K_n. Claim: M can be probabilistically embedded in tree metric spaces with distortion O(1).

In the χ-assisted online paging problem, let η(h,σ) denote the prediction error of predictor h on sequence σ. A predictor h is χ-accurate if η(h,σ) ≤ χ·Opt(σ) for all sequences σ. Claim: The PredMark algorithm achieves competitive ratio O(√χ) when using any χ-accurate predictor.

Let σ be a request sequence for online paging with N pages and cache size k. The sequence is partitioned into phases where each phase contains at most k distinct page requests. Claim: If a phase contains exactly k distinct page requests, then the next phase must begin with a request for a page not seen in the current phase.

Consider a traversal algorithm for MTS on a 2-point metric space with distance δ(1,2) = 1. The algorithm alternates between states 1 and 2. Claim: This traversal algorithm is exactly 4-competitive.

Let Alg be a deterministic online algorithm for some minimization problem P. We say that Alg is c-competitive if there exists α ≥ 0 such that Alg(σ) ≤ c·Opt(σ) + α for any instance σ. Claim: If an online algorithm Alg is c-competitive with additive constant α, then it is also (c+1)-competitive with additive constant 0.

In the ski rental problem, we have a parameter b > 1 representing the cost to buy ski equipment, while renting costs 1 EUR per day. Consider a deterministic algorithm that rents for exactly ⌊b/2⌋ days and then buys. Claim: This algorithm achieves a competitive ratio of at most 2.

Let Alg be any online marking algorithm for the paging problem with N pages and cache size k. We learned that Alg is k-competitive. Claim: Every marking algorithm has the same competitive ratio of exactly k.

Consider the online paging problem with N = k + 2 pages and cache size k. Let RandMark be the randomized marking algorithm that evicts an unmarked page chosen uniformly at random on each page fault. Claim: The competitive ratio of RandMark for this setting is O(log k).

Consider the UnifMTS algorithm on a uniform metric space with n points. During a phase, let s_1,...,s_n be the states ordered by non-decreasing saturation times. Claim: The algorithm can move from an unsaturated state to a saturated state within the same phase.

We say a metric space M has tree-width w if it can be isometrically embedded in a metric space obtained from distances in a tree with at most w leaves. Claim: There exists a deterministic online MTS algorithm with competitive ratio O(w) for metric spaces with tree-width w.

In the online Steiner tree problem, terminals arrive one by one and must be connected to the growing tree. Consider an instance where all terminals lie on a path graph. Claim: Any deterministic online algorithm has competitive ratio Ω(log n) even when the terminals form a path in the underlying graph.
Consider a metric space M obtained from distances in an unweighted complete graph K_n. Claim: M can be probabilistically embedded in tree metric spaces with distortion O(1).

In the χ-assisted online paging problem, let η(h,σ) denote the prediction error of predictor h on sequence σ. A predictor h is χ-accurate if η(h,σ) ≤ χ·Opt(σ) for all sequences σ. Claim: The PredMark algorithm achieves competitive ratio O(√χ) when using any χ-accurate predictor.

Let σ be a request sequence for online paging with N pages and cache size k. The sequence is partitioned into phases where each phase contains at most k distinct page requests. Claim: If a phase contains exactly k distinct page requests, then the next phase must begin with a request for a page not seen in the current phase.

Let H_k = 1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + ... + 1/k be the k-th harmonic number. We know that ln k < H_k ≤ 1 + ln k. Claim: For the RandMark algorithm, the expected number of page faults in a phase with m_i fresh pages is exactly m_i · H_k.
Consider a traversal algorithm for MTS on a 2-point metric space with distance δ(1,2) = 1. The algorithm alternates between states 1 and 2. Claim: This traversal algorithm is exactly 4-competitive.

A finite metric space M = (V,δ) has aspect ratio equal to max_{x,y∈V} δ(x,y) / min_{x≠y∈V} δ(x,y). Claim: Any metric space with aspect ratio ρ can be embedded in a uniform metric space with distortion at most ρ.
Consider the online paging problem with N = k+1 pages and cache size k. Claim: There exists a deterministic online algorithm with competitive ratio strictly less than k for this setting.

Yao's principle provides a method to establish lower bounds for randomized online algorithms by analyzing the performance of deterministic algorithms against a carefully chosen probability distribution over inputs. Claim: If we can show that every deterministic algorithm has expected cost at least c·E[Opt] under some input distribution, then every randomized algorithm has competitive ratio at least c.
